1
00:00:02,971 --> 00:00:04,238
[glass clinks]

2
00:00:04,271 --> 00:00:06,139
Obviously, I don't have
to remind you gentlemen

3
00:00:06,173 --> 00:00:08,008
that this meeting
never took place.

4
00:00:08,041 --> 00:00:10,210
Of course not,
Mayor Blossom.

5
00:00:10,244 --> 00:00:12,947
Has Ethel Muggs
been talking much

6
00:00:12,981 --> 00:00:14,749
since she's been
with the Sisters?

7
00:00:14,782 --> 00:00:16,316
Not a peep.

8
00:00:16,350 --> 00:00:19,988
Sister Woodhouse
has imposed
a vow of silence.

9
00:00:20,020 --> 00:00:21,523
Very good.

10
00:00:21,556 --> 00:00:23,123
-What about the PTA?
-[Featherhead]
Parents are still upset.

11
00:00:23,156 --> 00:00:24,926
It's all they talk about
at our meetings.

12
00:00:24,959 --> 00:00:26,528
Who killed
Mr. and Mrs. Muggs?

13
00:00:26,561 --> 00:00:30,030
As long as people remain
focused on this murder case,

14
00:00:30,063 --> 00:00:31,398
the more precarious

15
00:00:31,431 --> 00:00:35,369
our grasp
of the situation becomes.

16
00:00:35,402 --> 00:00:36,938
What's the
Sheriff's office doing?

17
00:00:36,971 --> 00:00:40,975
Tom is trying
to find this "milkman"

18
00:00:41,009 --> 00:00:42,042
and the murder weapon.

19
00:00:42,075 --> 00:00:43,611
Why is he doing that?

20
00:00:46,113 --> 00:00:50,217
I have the murder weapon
right here.

21
00:00:50,250 --> 00:00:51,619
What are you
getting at, Fredreich?

22
00:00:51,653 --> 00:00:53,320
[Dr. Werthers]
We have to stop rehashing

23
00:00:53,353 --> 00:00:56,056
the Muggs murder case
and start making sure

24
00:00:56,089 --> 00:00:58,960
that something like it
never happens again.

25
00:00:58,993 --> 00:01:02,329
In my extensive research,
in case after case,

26
00:01:02,362 --> 00:01:07,267
comic books
are the influencing factor
in most incidents

27
00:01:07,301 --> 00:01:11,039
of juvenile delinquency
and teen violence.

28
00:01:11,071 --> 00:01:14,441
They are
a moral scourge, gentlemen.

29
00:01:14,474 --> 00:01:17,612
<i>And their creators,</i>
<i>criminal degenerates.</i>

30
00:01:17,645 --> 00:01:20,848
That's what the PTA
should be talking about.

31
00:01:20,882 --> 00:01:21,749
Comic books.

32
00:01:22,750 --> 00:01:24,886
Not the Muggs.

33
00:01:24,919 --> 00:01:30,290
And I believe
I know exactly how
to make that happen.

34
00:01:32,927 --> 00:01:33,795
[typewriter clacks]

35
00:01:35,295 --> 00:01:39,033
Well, look who strolls in
whenever his heart desires.

36
00:01:39,067 --> 00:01:40,034
What do you want, kid?

37
00:01:40,068 --> 00:01:41,335
I was just
in the neighborhood.

38
00:01:42,070 --> 00:01:43,136
Where is everyone?

39
00:01:43,170 --> 00:01:44,438
They're all out
with a stomach bug.

40
00:01:44,471 --> 00:01:46,106
Now I'm under more water
than the <i>Titanic.</i>

41
00:01:46,139 --> 00:01:47,274
-Can I help?
-[typing]

42
00:01:47,307 --> 00:01:49,077
I need a full issue...

43
00:01:49,109 --> 00:01:50,177
I can do that.

44
00:01:50,210 --> 00:01:51,478
...written by tomorrow morning.

45
00:01:51,512 --> 00:01:53,014
Yeah, that's no problem,
Mr. Fieldstone.

46
00:01:53,047 --> 00:01:54,448
I'm fast.
I'm a great speller.

47
00:01:54,481 --> 00:01:56,818
Four stories.
Seven pages each.

48
00:01:56,851 --> 00:01:58,086
Zero margin for error.

49
00:01:58,118 --> 00:01:59,186
[Jughead]
I'll write 'em on spec.

50
00:01:59,219 --> 00:02:00,922
If you like them, then great.

51
00:02:00,955 --> 00:02:03,625
And if not,
there's plenty more
where that came from.

52
00:02:03,658 --> 00:02:05,292
Right.

53
00:02:05,325 --> 00:02:08,096
If you have trouble
coming up with some ideas,

54
00:02:08,128 --> 00:02:09,998
take these springboards.

55
00:02:10,031 --> 00:02:11,331
Talk them through with Bernie.

56
00:02:11,365 --> 00:02:13,467
I will. Won't let you down.

57
00:02:14,035 --> 00:02:15,268
Bernie.

58
00:02:17,905 --> 00:02:21,408
Gosh, Bernie,
all these stories
have been done to death.

59
00:02:21,441 --> 00:02:24,078
Aren't there
any original ideas anymore?

60
00:02:24,112 --> 00:02:25,479
Says the teenager?

61
00:02:26,781 --> 00:02:29,517
Bernie, you're a genius.

62
00:02:29,550 --> 00:02:33,286
What about stories
about teenagers
and high school?

63
00:02:33,320 --> 00:02:35,690
Pep Comics doesn't have
any of those, right?

64
00:02:35,723 --> 00:02:36,557
Uh... [sighs]

65
00:02:36,591 --> 00:02:37,992
Al says he doesn't
relate to them.

66
00:02:38,026 --> 00:02:40,293
But teenagers
do buy our books.

67
00:02:40,327 --> 00:02:42,530
Well, shucks,
me and my friends do.

68
00:02:42,563 --> 00:02:44,599
[snaps finger]
What about a narrator

69
00:02:44,632 --> 00:02:49,704
that's actually
a witchy lunch lady,
or a creepy janitor?

70
00:02:49,737 --> 00:02:52,974
We can call it
"Homeroom of Horrors."

71
00:02:53,007 --> 00:02:54,174
Huh?

72
00:02:54,207 --> 00:02:55,777
You think Mr. Fieldstone
will bite?

73
00:02:55,810 --> 00:02:56,744
Sure.

74
00:02:57,177 --> 00:02:58,546
Give it a whirl.

75
00:03:04,986 --> 00:03:06,120
[door opens]

76
00:03:06,154 --> 00:03:07,855
There's my little
tortured genius.

77
00:03:07,889 --> 00:03:09,657
-[door closes]
-Think you could
take a break

78
00:03:09,691 --> 00:03:11,659
from writing the next
great American novel

79
00:03:11,693 --> 00:03:14,829
and take this glamour gal
to go see a fun flick?

80
00:03:14,862 --> 00:03:16,097
[typing rapidly]

81
00:03:16,130 --> 00:03:17,431
<i>Diabolique</i> is playing
at the Babylonium,

82
00:03:17,464 --> 00:03:20,168
and I know
you don't mind subtitles.

83
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:22,136
Ooh. Could we go
tomorrow, maybe?

84
00:03:22,170 --> 00:03:23,470
I'm on deadline.

85
00:03:23,504 --> 00:03:26,174
Al's asked me to write
an entire issue by morning.

86
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:28,442
An entire issue?

87
00:03:28,475 --> 00:03:30,978
Sounds like
a bit of a coup for you.

88
00:03:31,012 --> 00:03:32,212
Yeah, it is.

89
00:03:32,245 --> 00:03:33,614
But it's also
a lot of pressure.

90
00:03:33,648 --> 00:03:35,717
Though, if I do a bang up job
on these pages tonight,

91
00:03:35,750 --> 00:03:37,952
Fieldstone could ask me
to be one of his go-to's.

92
00:03:38,886 --> 00:03:40,054
Okay. Okay.

93
00:03:40,088 --> 00:03:42,623
My French thriller about
murderous schoolteachers
can wait.

94
00:03:42,657 --> 00:03:46,027
But since I'm here,
maybe I can help you.

95
00:03:46,060 --> 00:03:47,128
How far have you gotten?

96
00:03:47,161 --> 00:03:49,097
I'm almost done
with my first story.

97
00:03:49,130 --> 00:03:51,199
I'm all ears.
What's it about?

98
00:03:51,231 --> 00:03:52,332
Sports-themed.

99
00:03:52,365 --> 00:03:54,102
Because what's scarier
than gym class?

100
00:03:54,135 --> 00:03:55,335
And it has a narrator,

101
00:03:55,368 --> 00:03:57,105
like all of my yell yarns will,

102
00:03:57,138 --> 00:03:59,974
um, called the Key-Keeper.

103
00:04:00,007 --> 00:04:03,077
-I had one of the artists
at Pep Comics do a mockup.
-[chuckles]

104
00:04:03,111 --> 00:04:04,244
It's pretty nifty, right?

105
00:04:04,277 --> 00:04:06,681
The niftiest.
Looks like a real charmer.

106
00:04:09,050 --> 00:04:14,354
[Key-Keeper] <i>Well, well, well,</i>
<i>if it isn't another</i>
<i>problem child.</i>

107
00:04:14,387 --> 00:04:17,158
You're looking for a little
mischief and mayhem,

108
00:04:17,191 --> 00:04:18,325
aren't you?

109
00:04:18,358 --> 00:04:21,195
Well, maybe I can be
of some assistance.

110
00:04:21,229 --> 00:04:22,530
[keys jangling]

111
00:04:23,263 --> 00:04:25,900
I'm the Key-Keeper,
you see?

112
00:04:25,933 --> 00:04:30,437
The midnight custodian
of this schoolhouse of horrors.

113
00:04:30,470 --> 00:04:33,306
Come along
and let's wake the dead

114
00:04:33,340 --> 00:04:35,243
with a real spine twister,
shall we?

115
00:04:35,275 --> 00:04:36,644
[keys jangling]

116
00:04:38,012 --> 00:04:39,213
[door unlocks]

117
00:04:39,247 --> 00:04:40,982
I call
this sordid little tale...

118
00:04:41,883 --> 00:04:44,252
[Key-Keeper reading]

119
00:04:44,317 --> 00:04:45,352
[whistle blows]

120
00:04:45,385 --> 00:04:46,721
[Key-Keeper]
<i>Every team has one,</i>

121
00:04:46,754 --> 00:04:48,723
<i>the runt, the klutz,</i>
<i>the pip-squeak.</i>

122
00:04:48,756 --> 00:04:50,323
<i>On the Bulldogs</i>
<i>basketball team,</i>

123
00:04:50,357 --> 00:04:52,794
<i>that half pint was</i>

124
00:04:52,827 --> 00:04:54,829
<i>Dilton Doiley,</i>

125
00:04:54,862 --> 00:04:58,866
<i>who was short,</i>
<i>near-sighted</i>
<i>and uncoordinated.</i>

126
00:05:01,068 --> 00:05:04,071
<i>At the end</i>
<i>of one particularly</i>
<i>grueling practice,</i>

127
00:05:04,105 --> 00:05:07,909
<i>Coach Kleats</i>
<i>had the team line up</i>
<i>for free throws.</i>

128
00:05:07,942 --> 00:05:11,946
<i>No one could leave</i>
<i>until everyone</i>
<i>had made a basket.</i>

129
00:05:11,979 --> 00:05:16,217
<i>But Dilton couldn't</i>
<i>make a shot</i>
<i>to save his life.</i>

130
00:05:16,250 --> 00:05:18,286
Come on, Doiley.

131
00:05:18,318 --> 00:05:20,320
Get your head in the game.

132
00:05:22,089 --> 00:05:23,090
[ball bounces]

133
00:05:26,393 --> 00:05:28,696
Maybe you need
a little motivation.

134
00:05:30,231 --> 00:05:32,066
[whistle blows]

135
00:05:32,099 --> 00:05:34,001
[Key-Keeper] <i>Coach Kleats</i>
<i>had the other players</i>

136
00:05:34,035 --> 00:05:39,240
<i>start running laps</i>
<i>until Dilton sunk one</i>
<i>lousy bucket.</i>

137
00:05:39,273 --> 00:05:40,842
You're a dead man, Doiley.

138
00:05:41,474 --> 00:05:43,277
[Key-Keeper] <i>Poor Dilton.</i>

139
00:05:43,311 --> 00:05:48,916
<i>He would soon learn</i>
<i>the true meaning</i>
<i>of the term "foul play."</i>

140
00:05:50,383 --> 00:05:52,820
The hell is wrong
with you, Doiley?

141
00:05:54,155 --> 00:05:55,455
I'm sorry, fellas.

142
00:05:55,488 --> 00:05:58,226
I... I'm trying my best.

143
00:05:58,259 --> 00:05:59,594
Why are you even here

144
00:05:59,627 --> 00:06:02,462
if you can't make
one stinking basket?

145
00:06:02,495 --> 00:06:04,497
I just wanted to be
part of a team.

146
00:06:04,532 --> 00:06:06,466
Then be the damn water boy.

147
00:06:07,268 --> 00:06:08,368
[scoffs]

148
00:06:08,401 --> 00:06:10,938
It's like what
Coach Kleats said...

149
00:06:10,972 --> 00:06:12,974
"You've got to get
your head in the game."

150
00:06:14,075 --> 00:06:16,310
How... how do I do that?

151
00:06:16,344 --> 00:06:18,112
Maybe a night
stuffed in a locker

152
00:06:18,145 --> 00:06:19,213
will help you figure it out.

153
00:06:19,247 --> 00:06:21,215
What? No. Guys, guys, guys.

154
00:06:21,249 --> 00:06:23,284
Please, please,
don't do that.

155
00:06:23,317 --> 00:06:24,451
No. Please! Please!

156
00:06:24,484 --> 00:06:25,418
You don't understand.

157
00:06:25,452 --> 00:06:27,255
Stop! I can't.

158
00:06:27,288 --> 00:06:29,590
-Hey, guys, maybe this isn't
such a good idea.
-[Dilton] Don't leave me here!

159
00:06:29,624 --> 00:06:32,392
-Stuff it, Andrews.
-[Dilton crying]
I can't be here alone.

160
00:06:32,425 --> 00:06:34,262
-Please. I can't.
-Doiley's got to learn.

161
00:06:34,295 --> 00:06:36,496
He's gonna start
pulling his weight.

162
00:06:39,333 --> 00:06:41,002
Or we're gonna murder him.

163
00:06:44,071 --> 00:06:45,106
No! Don't go!

164
00:06:45,139 --> 00:06:46,574
Please! Please! Don't go!

165
00:06:46,607 --> 00:06:49,277
Don't leave me here!
I can't do this. No!

166
00:06:49,310 --> 00:06:50,778
No! Please!

167
00:06:50,811 --> 00:06:54,115
[Key-Keeper] <i>What these</i>
<i>merciless jocks didn't know</i>

168
00:06:54,148 --> 00:07:01,589
<i>was that</i>
<i>Dilton Doiley was born</i>
<i>morbidly claustrophobic.</i>

169
00:07:03,456 --> 00:07:04,859
[birds chirping]

170
00:07:06,093 --> 00:07:08,095
[breathing uneasily]

171
00:07:08,129 --> 00:07:10,264
[door opens]

172
00:07:10,298 --> 00:07:14,402
[Key-Keeper] <i>So, by the time</i>
<i>the day shift found</i>
<i>and released Dilton</i>

173
00:07:14,434 --> 00:07:17,204
<i>the next morning...</i>

174
00:07:17,238 --> 00:07:22,442
<i>Dilton had suffered</i>
<i>a complete psychotic break.</i>

175
00:07:24,312 --> 00:07:27,248
<i>He was a changed man.</i>

176
00:07:27,281 --> 00:07:29,884
<i>A madman, you might say.</i>

177
00:07:29,917 --> 00:07:34,221
<i>Hell-bent on revenge</i>
<i>against the Bulldogs.</i>

178
00:07:36,057 --> 00:07:37,758
[glass breaks]

179
00:07:37,792 --> 00:07:39,994
[Key-Keeper] <i>Then it was just</i>
<i>a matter of lying in wait</i>

180
00:07:40,027 --> 00:07:43,496
<i>for his teammates</i>
<i>to reconvene</i>
<i>for basketball practice</i>

181
00:07:43,531 --> 00:07:45,900
<i>later that afternoon.</i>

182
00:07:47,068 --> 00:07:50,171
<i>Luckily, Dilton had</i>
<i>the perfect hidey-hole</i>

183
00:07:50,204 --> 00:07:53,841
<i>from which to pop out</i>
<i>and surprise his teammates.</i>

184
00:07:54,942 --> 00:07:57,511
<i>After which Dilton</i>
<i>could dedicate himself</i>

185
00:07:57,545 --> 00:08:01,382
<i>to perfecting</i>
<i>his free throw technique.</i>

186
00:08:01,415 --> 00:08:03,050
Gotta keep
my head in the game.

187
00:08:04,385 --> 00:08:05,653
Gotta keep my head
in the game.

188
00:08:05,686 --> 00:08:07,221
[Kleats] Attaboy, Doiley!

189
00:08:28,376 --> 00:08:30,711
Help! [yelling]

190
00:08:30,745 --> 00:08:33,481
Gotta keep
my head in the game.

191
00:08:33,514 --> 00:08:35,616
Gotta keep
my head in the game.

192
00:08:36,484 --> 00:08:38,753
Gotta keep
my head in the game.

193
00:08:38,786 --> 00:08:40,755
Gotta keep
my head in the game.

194
00:08:40,788 --> 00:08:42,390
Gotta keep
my head in the game.

195
00:08:42,423 --> 00:08:43,824
[screeching]

196
00:08:45,559 --> 00:08:46,627
[woman screaming]

197
00:08:49,230 --> 00:08:50,498
Good for Dilton.

198
00:08:50,531 --> 00:08:52,466
Those awful bullies
got what was coming to them.

199
00:08:52,500 --> 00:08:53,667
Exactly.

200
00:08:53,701 --> 00:08:55,369
And you see, that's what
nitwits like Werthers

201
00:08:55,403 --> 00:08:56,971
just don't understand.

202
00:08:57,004 --> 00:08:58,172
What, exactly?

203
00:08:58,205 --> 00:08:59,774
Well, that these
so-called "degenerate" comics

204
00:08:59,807 --> 00:09:02,476
are actually bite-sized
morality tales.

205
00:09:02,511 --> 00:09:03,711
Especially those that involve

206
00:09:03,744 --> 00:09:05,846
Julian Blossom getting
his head chopped off.

207
00:09:05,880 --> 00:09:07,848
I mean, you joke,
but it's true.

208
00:09:07,882 --> 00:09:10,484
Yes, comics can be
over the top
and bloody sometimes,

209
00:09:10,519 --> 00:09:13,654
but in these stories,
people that break the rules
get punished.

210
00:09:13,687 --> 00:09:15,689
People who are cruel
to others get punished.

211
00:09:15,723 --> 00:09:18,092
People who have lustful sex
get punished.

212
00:09:18,125 --> 00:09:20,394
Lustful sex, did you say?

213
00:09:20,428 --> 00:09:22,463
Tell me more
about that, Juggiekins.

214
00:09:22,496 --> 00:09:24,398
[chuckles] I've got a tale
for you.

215
00:09:24,432 --> 00:09:26,000
And it starts,
believe it or not,

216
00:09:26,033 --> 00:09:28,402
-on a dark and stormy night...
-[thunder rumbling]

217
00:09:28,436 --> 00:09:32,773
With a flat tire
near an isolated mansion.

218
00:09:32,807 --> 00:09:36,677
<i>And a young, strapping man</i>
<i>in need of assistance.</i>

219
00:09:36,710 --> 00:09:38,679
[thunder rumbling]

220
00:09:40,781 --> 00:09:42,183
Yes?

221
00:09:42,216 --> 00:09:43,217
May I help you?

222
00:09:43,250 --> 00:09:44,885
I'm sorry to bother you
at this hour, ma'am,

223
00:09:44,919 --> 00:09:48,456
but my hot rod got
a flat tire down the road.

224
00:09:48,489 --> 00:09:50,257
Must've ran over a nail
or something.

225
00:09:50,291 --> 00:09:51,560
[Nana Rose] Oh, how dreadful.

226
00:09:51,592 --> 00:09:55,162
And now here you are, stranded,
you poor dear.

227
00:09:55,196 --> 00:09:56,764
Why don't you come inside?

228
00:09:56,797 --> 00:10:00,234
You can use our telephone
to call the garage.

229
00:10:00,267 --> 00:10:04,305
At this hour?
Oh, they'll be closed, ma'am.

230
00:10:04,338 --> 00:10:07,608
Would it be too much trouble
if I stayed the night?

231
00:10:07,641 --> 00:10:09,844
That way, in the morning,
I can call the garage

232
00:10:09,877 --> 00:10:11,345
and I'll be out of your hair.

233
00:10:11,378 --> 00:10:12,446
[thunder rumbling]

234
00:10:12,480 --> 00:10:14,248
I suppose. But...

235
00:10:14,281 --> 00:10:17,151
I'm afraid the storm
has knocked out our power.

236
00:10:17,184 --> 00:10:19,386
But you can warm yourself
by the fire.

237
00:10:19,420 --> 00:10:21,188
Well, come in.

238
00:10:21,222 --> 00:10:22,323
Come in.

239
00:10:22,356 --> 00:10:23,657
Oh, you look a fright.

240
00:10:23,691 --> 00:10:24,859
[thunder rumbling]

241
00:10:26,528 --> 00:10:30,931
[Key-Keeper]
<i>They say a picture</i>
